explanation:
For determining whether any statements in OS_MutSemCreate_Impl are dead code you must know which operations have observable side-effects, which can be compiled away, and whether argument expressions are evaluated. Brief rationale for each required symbol:

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro that obtains impl from the table. Its expansion may perform validation or side-effects; whether it evaluates its arguments or can be optimized away affects if the lookup (and any sub-operations) is dead.
- OS_impl_mutex_table: The object/table passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Its structure/definition can affect the macro expansion and whether impl is valid/used.
- OS_impl_mutex_internal_record_t: Type of impl; needed to know the presence and type of impl->id and whether accessing impl has side-effects or is unused.
- OS_object_token_t: Token type used as input to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to know whether dereferencing *token has side-effects or is necessary.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Appears in the static call graph and is likely used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its behavior (side-effects, validations) affects whether the table lookup is a meaningful operation.
- pthread_mutexattr_init: Must know its semantics and side-effects (initializes attr and can fail) to decide if calling it is necessary for observable behavior.
- pthread_mutexattr_setprotocol: Its semantics (sets protocol on attribute) matter for observable behavior (priority inheritance); removing it could change runtime behavior.
- pthread_mutexattr_settype: Sets mutex type (RECURSIVE) — this has observable effects on mutex behavior and so cannot be assumed dead without its definition/behavior.
- pthread_mutex_init: Creates/initializes the actual mutex; clearly has observable side-effects and must be considered when judging dead code.
- PTHREAD_PRIO_INHERIT: Value used for setprotocol; needed to know what behavior is being enabled and whether the call is meaningful.
- PTHREAD_MUTEX_RECURSIVE: Value used for settype; needed to know the intended mutex semantics and whether removing the settype call would alter behavior.
- pthread_mutex_t: Type of impl->id; knowledge of the underlying type/representation may be needed to assess side-effects of initialization and whether impl->id is actually used elsewhere.
- OS_DEBUG: Logging macro/function. Important because if OS_DEBUG expands to nothing (or to a no-op that does not evaluate its arguments) then the associated OS_ObjectId*/strerror calls are dead (not evaluated). If OS_DEBUG evaluates its args, those calls are live.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: Used only inside debug messages; whether it has side-effects (or is removed when OS_DEBUG is disabled) determines whether those calls are dead.
- OS_ObjectIdToInteger: Ditto — used in debug prints; required to know if its evaluation is observable.
- strerror: Standard library call that may be evaluated as part of debug messages; whether it is invoked or optimized away depends on OS_DEBUG expansion.
- OS_SEM_FAILURE: The error return value used on failure paths; required to see whether the early-return branches change observable behavior (removing the failing branch could alter return codes).
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return value; needed to determine the observable outcome of the function and whether removing operations would change that outcome.

With these symbols (macro definitions, types, and function semantics) the next analyzer can determine which statements have observable effects (e.g., mutex initialization and attribute changes) and which are only for logging or could be optimized away; only then can it decide if any executed operations in OS_MutSemCreate_Impl qualify as dead code under the MISRA rule.
